english:
  title: Afterword to the Map of the Three Kingdoms
  author: Lee Cham
  language: eng
  text: 'When the Ming established its imperial succession, it embraced all four seas, so that even a single foot of earth and inch of sky entered the registers of the realm. The vastness of such maps and the breadth of territories surely required those appointed to such stewardship. In ancient Zhou, the Grand Minister of Earth kept the maps of all lands beneath heaven, thereby knowing the measures of territory completely. The maps of the Office of Regional Descriptions grew even more refined. When Han conquered Qin, Xiao He was first to gather the maps and charts, and only then did he come to know the narrowness of the world''s passages and the many small differences in its populations. Emperor Guangwu unrolled maps of territory and pointing to Deng Yu said, "The prefectures and counties of all under heaven are thus arranged—now we finally see them." Thus the value of maps needs no further praise. In our realm, the prefectures and counties appeared only roughly in maps, lacking detail, so none could verify them. Only after the unification of the Three Kingdoms did there appear the Map of Goryeo, though we know not whose hand drew it. Observing its mountains: from Baekdu they wind and descend until at Iron Ridge they suddenly rise as Pungak, doubling back as Great and Small Baek, then as Bamboo Ridge, Cock''s Crest, Three River Ridge—turning toward Yang Mountain where the Central Peak stands, stretching toward Cloud Summit where the earth''s geography completes itself. The earth''s axis reaches here and passes not beyond the sea southward. Pure and clear vapors gather and concentrate here, so these mountains rise supremely high—no other peaks can match their majesty. Waters flowing west from this spine are called the Sal, the Paek, the Bireul, the Rimjin, the Han, the Xiong—all reaching the Western Sea. Only from the eastern slope does the Gaya flow southward alone. Primal breath condenses and crystallizes; where mountains end, waters encircle and bind. Seeing this map alone reveals the domain of wind-spirit and the boundaries of prefectures and counties. In the age of Three Kingdoms, they divided and splintered territories, none achieving lasting unity, until the ancestor of the Wang house, armored and blade in hand, won through fire and water to accomplish unification. Yet in its later days, decline grew severe, and the old works of ancestors could not be preserved. Heaven''s mandate and human hearts turned elsewhere. Now our sovereign lord, possessed of brilliant wisdom and heroic resolve, has encountered the fortune of sage-kings rising once in five hundred years. Responding to heaven and following human hearts, he has established Eastern civilization anew, recovered the ancient name of Joseon, and set the new capital at Hanyang. To examine this map and verify it—that time is now. In the year Byeongja, dwelling in the new capital and reading the History of Three Kingdoms, I found its abundance burdensome. Presuming upon my narrow sight, I dared to abridge and arrange it into three volumes, and moreover examined our realm''s maps, divided and organized them into three sections, affixing each as a chapter heading. All prefectures and counties I have recorded in their ancient names with annotations in their present forms. Only for territories north of the Sakdae and west of Pyongyang, which appear not in geographical records, have I recorded them solely by their present names. As for maps showing separation and unity—this too has its principle. One and two are the generative numbers of heaven and earth, becoming odd and even to produce all things. Three too is a generative number. When it becomes one, unity may not hold; when it becomes three, separation cannot occur. Seeing three, we understand how difficult true unification is; seeing one, we grasp that maintaining order is no easy task. Thus this arrangement of three proves not without benefit to the instruction of the throne.'
  footnotes:
    - The author refers to the establishment of the Joseon Dynasty and the move of the capital to Hanyang (present-day Seoul) by King Taejo. The year Byeongja refers to 1396.
    - 'The cosmological numerology here draws on traditional East Asian philosophy: one represents unity and heaven, two represents the duality that generates creation, and three represents the three realms (heaven, earth, humanity) or the trinity of existence.'
    - The mountains and rivers named represent the major geographical features of the Korean peninsula, establishing Korea's distinct place in the cosmos and its centrality to the author's understanding of proper order.
